title: For Sale/Trade:  T/C CONTENDER COMPLETE 2 BARREL SET FOR LG/SM GAME
postcontent:
I have for sale a Contender Pistol that I bought new around 20-25 years ago. I have taken extrem care of it and it would stand side by side with a new gun. As most know the T/C's desirability is that it is a set of components that can be purchased separately and added to, or changed at will. My gun is the Super 14 version, in 30-30 Win, and .22 LR. I shoot around 5-6 rounds through the 30-30 barrel every year and around 50 rounds through the .22. At the beginning of dear season I take it out and put 5 rounds through it at 50 yards to check my scope is still on and then after seeing it put all 5 right dead above the bulls-eye where i want them, I put it in its holster and only fire it again if I'm hunting and get a shot. I have not shot anything with it latly. The last three years I have took deer with bow, muzzle loader, and my 30-40 Krag, but have not had one come out while caring the contender. That said, you give me a 150 gr bullet from any maker and I'll show you how to drop the biggest dear in the woods at 100 yds even wearing my bi-focals, haha. Everybody has their cartridge they like in a Contender and many go for the more exotic rounds, but I can attest from 20+ years of owning and shooting one, that the 30-30 round is as good as it gets. 1st: you can buy 30-30 150 gr bullets about anywhere. I went to the gun show out by McConnell here just a while back and picked up three full boxes for 10.00 a box. 2nd: If its any bigger, or hotter round than a 30-30, I don't want to shoot it out of a Contender anyway. 3rd: I usually hunt the Contender in the woods and very seldom get a shot with it over 100 yrds and the majority of the time its more like 20-30, but I know it will shoot 200 if I want to and keep it sighted for 100 dead on. I don't use the 30-30 for target practice, or plinking because it just has more recoil than I like to shoot for long periods of time, but its perfect for hunting and somehow I never feel the recoil when shooting game, haha. Now before I move on to the other other barrel let me tell you one more thing. Can you say here piggy piggy? You want a fun shooting hog gun, here it is. it will drop one like a bad habit. Secondly I have a .22 barrel same size and weight. The best fun you can have with it is to hunt you tree stand either before, or after deer season for squirrels. I don’t know if you ever have shot a 14 inch .22 bull barrel with precision adjusted sights, but you can head shoot them at 25 yards. I hunt through deer season and pattern the squirrels around my stand and then the week following deer season I put the whammy on them. I still have 3 in the freezer right now. What’s nice is you can shoot the .22 all day cheep and it has zero recoil in this gun, and then switch over to the 30-30 to hunt and never think about recoil. Right before hunting season sight in the 30-30 then switch barrels and take the .22 to the indoor range and shoot it for the evening, swap out the barrels and go hunting. Now for the scope it’s a Leupold M8-4X Extended E.R. Pistol Scope. I see them listed on gun sites for around $200.00. I like the 4 power on this gun. I is a good mix for me between target acquisition and magnification. I would use less magnification on a target pistol that I shot a at close range like indoors, but for big game hunting, its just right, and I pick up my target pretty fast with it. I adjusted it years ago out at the rifle range at Cheney Lake and have never had to adjust it since. I have shot 5-6 different brands of ammo, whatever the cheapest 150 gr they have the day I need some and it all shoots well. I changed out the factory forend with a 40.00 Pachmayr because I liked it better. title: For Sale/Trade:  Original 3-Point Adjustable Stock From XM177 (?) CAR-15 (?) Need AR LPK or Magpul Stock
postcontent:
I  recently was searching for a stock for my AR build and came across this one. Not my first choice, but it was all i could find at the time. I purchased it, and the guy i got it from asked if i needed any other parts. It turned out that his father had passed away and left him this stock along with a ton of other original M16A1-A2, XM-177, CAR-15 parts but he had no idea what any of it was. He even had 3 fully build M16A2's that his father had built and saved after he returned from duty! He's sitting on a gold mine and doesn't even realize it yet!

Anyway, i figured this stock would be great for someone that is doing a retro build, or maybe even used an actual XM-177 when they were in the service and maybe prefer this style stock!

The guy claimed that it was brand new, and for being roughly 30 years old, it does look pretty well taken care of. My guess is, he removed it whenever the M16 was issued to him, and maybe placed a different stock on it. Or this could have possibly been a spare he purchased for a later build he planned on doing, who knows. 

I believe it is a mil-spec stock, and mil-spec buffer. Not sure if they even had a commercial back then, but the buffer is not slanted at all in the back. 

It's not the aluminum model, but is more like a high density poly material. Still looks and feels amazing though, and will definitely withstand some blows!

I CAN also include the original buffer kit if you need that as well!It will include, buffer, buffer tube, buffer sprint, castle ring, and the other standard locking ring.

Trades:
AR Lower Parts Kit (complete kit with grip)
Magpul MOE or ACS in black or Tan
Cash (offer, no clue what it's worth.) If it's colt it would be worth a couple hundred, but i can't verify that it is colt.

Cell for call or text - REDACTED

I'm constantly moving from class to home to work to class, etc. so if you don't catch me just leave a message and let me know that your calling about my armslist ad and ill get back with you when i leave wherever i am! Texts work better, but i realize some people don't/can't text, i am perfectly fine with either choice. It is just easier for texts!

title: For Trade:  My ENTIRE Custom T-Shirt/Clothing Business For Your?? Heat Presses, Thermal Printers, Thermal Scanners, Graphics Machines +
postcontent:
I recently acquired this setup from a relative that passed away. She stopped traveling to trade shows last year when she fell deathly sick, and just recently passed away. Nobody really knew how to run these machines but her, so they gave them to me. I have figured out the basics, and tested all equipment to make it works 100%, and it all performed perfectly! I am just a busy college student though, with a very small apartment and no room or time to learn this equipment well enough to start operating a business.

I remember when my friend bought into all of this stuff, and i know she paid well over $45,000 for it all. Is it worth that now, most definitely not, nor will i be trying to get that out of it. I have successfully found about half of the machines that are in my possession on websites like ebay, craigslist and other forums that recently sold. The ones i did find range from 200$ to 800$ so there is still quite a bit of value in this stuff if you plan on selling it down the road. The main machine was 23,000 alone and i can't seem to find any info about them at all online really. None that have sold or are up for sale either.

But anyways, on to the equipment. Here is what i have up for trade

QLT Futura 100 Graphic Design Machine (This is the supposed $23,000 box, in it's prime of course) With the QLT software disk (Have found a TON of people looking for this disk. The machine won't work without it from what i've read! Allows you to do color modification to images with the turn of a knob (actually 5 knobs).

Shinko CHC-545 Thermal Printing system. This box is responsible for heating your wax image from the thermal paper to a heat transfer sheet to place on your products (T-Shirts, Hoodys, Sweatpants, Buttons, Mugs, etc!) I have found a few in non-working condition, or beat up shape for 400-600$. Mine is fully working and ready to print. Even have a roll or two of the thermal film.

Hitachi-VY170 Color Video Printer. I believe this is what operates the screen, kindof like a brain for the Futura 100 Box if i had to guess. You can load smaller thermal film into the front of this. This machine could be responsible for just the smaller items like buttons, hats and such. 

Sony UY-T35V Color Video Scanner. I would assume this scans your logo/photo/image onto either the Hitachi or Shinko for transfer to a transfer paper.

Hix Basix B-400 BT Heat Press. Hix no longer produces these, however some sites still have the base model B-400 for 900$ new. This one is an upgraded model with timer and thermometer. Looks only slightly used, heating element is great, thermometer is 100% spot on.

ex/press swivel press. This is a slightly smaller press, maybe used for easy maneuverability for the smaller products to be printed on. It swivels to the side, or pushes alright down onto the heat board. Heating element is flawless, but this is press shows a bit more wear then the basix. 

Trintron RGB Television. The futura machine will only display images on RGB screens, or other screens with a special adapter. This one is made almost specifically for the futura and will work as your editing monitor. You could probably use a newer monitor if you could find an adapter to convert the colors to RGB.

Panasonic KS-222 Camera w/ Tripod, camera mounts, upgraded lense, extra bright flash unit on top. This thing hooks directly up to the futura for image editing! Back when my friend ran this portable business she would do portraits of grand children, children and other people to print onto a shirt. 

There are endless possibilities with this equipment. There is some great potential if you'd like to get your feet wet in the custom t-shirt printing industry, at roughly 1/20 of the price it would cost to buy the latest equipment!

If interested please call/text REDACTED for more info! I would be willing to part one of the heat presses for smaller items if you would like! I am very bust with college, work and everything else going on in my life so if i do not answer, please leave a voicemail and ill get right back to you! Text however is the easiest form of contact, or e-mail!
